'''Hoshi Matsuri''' (星まつり or 星祭り) is a {{ill|Buddhist|ja|仏教|12=draft}} ritual held on occasions such as the Lunar New Year, {{ill|Risshun|ja|立春|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Winter Solstice|ja|冬至|12=draft}}.<ref>In Taoism, the ritual was originally conducted on the Winter Solstice and had no connection to Risshun or the Lunar New Year. It was only after being incorporated into Buddhism that it began to be observed on these additional dates.</ref> The purpose of this ritual is to ward off various disasters affecting both the state and individuals. It is also known as "'''Star Memorial Service'''” (星供養, Hoshikuyō), "'''Star Offering'''” (星供, Hoshiku), or the "'''Big Dipper Ritual'''” (北斗法, Hokutohō).

In {{ill|Esoteric Buddhism|ja|密教|12=draft}}, which belongs to the later teachings of the {{ill|Mahayana|ja|大乗|12=draft}} tradition, deities such as {{ill|Ichiji Kinrin Butchō|ja|一字金輪仏頂|12=draft}} (also known as {{ill|Dainichi Kinrin|ja|大日金輪|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shaka Kinrin|ja|釈迦金輪|12=draft}}) are enshrined in mandalas like the {{ill|Star Mandala|ja|星曼荼羅|12=draft}}. Other examples include the {{ill|Seven-Star Nyoirin Mandala|ja|七星如意輪曼荼羅|12=draft}} with {{ill|Nyoirin Kannon|ja|如意輪観音|12=draft}} as the principal deity and the {{ill|Myōken Mandala|ja|妙見曼荼羅|12=draft}} featuring {{ill|Myōken Bosatsu|ja|妙見菩薩|12=draft}}. These mandalas are central to rituals and ceremonies that honor the year's guiding star (当年星, tōnenjō)<ref>"Tōnenjō" is also referred to as "Tōnen Zokusei" (当年属星).</ref> and the natal star (本命星, honmyōjō).<ref>Although the term "honmyōsei" is also used in {{ill|Nine Star Ki|ja|九星気学|12=draft}}, in this context it refers to stars from the {{ill|Big Dipper|ja|北斗七星|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Nine Luminaries|ja|九曜星|12=draft}}, rather than the nine stars of Ki astrology.</ref>

Originally, this ritual was part of the {{ill|Taoist|ja|道教|12=draft}} Winter Solstice festival and had no relation to {{ill|Indian Buddhism|ja|インドの仏教|12=draft}}. However, it was later incorporated into Esoteric Buddhism, where it was adapted and reinterpreted within a Buddhist framework.

In Esoteric astrology, as represented by the Star Mandala, both esoteric rituals and celestial astrology form the core principles. One of the nine {{ill|Navagraha|ja|九曜|12=draft}} stars or the seven stars of the Big Dipper is assigned as a person's natal star (本命星), believed to govern their destiny.

The star that influences a person's fortune for the year is called the "Tōnen Zokusei" (当年属星). The ritual aims to honor these stars, pray for individual well-being, and eliminate misfortunes. Various temples across Japan hold Hoshi Matsuri and Star Memorial ceremonies.

