In {{ill|Esoteric Buddhism|ja|密教|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Esoteric Buddhism|qq=}}, which belongs to the later teachings of the {{ill|Mahayana|ja|大乗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mahayana|qq=}} tradition, deities such as {{ill|Ichiji Kinrin Butchō|ja|一字金輪仏頂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichiji Kinrin Butchō|qq=}} (also known as {{ill|Dainichi Kinrin|ja|大日金輪|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dainichi Kinrin|qq=}} and {{ill|Shaka Kinrin|ja|釈迦金輪|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shaka Kinrin|qq=}}) are enshrined in mandalas like the {{ill|Star Mandala|ja|星曼荼羅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Star Mandala|qq=}}. Other examples include the {{ill|Seven-Star Nyoirin Mandala|ja|七星如意輪曼荼羅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seven-Star Nyoirin Mandala|qq=}} with {{ill|Nyoirin Kannon|ja|如意輪観音|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nyoirin Kannon|qq=}} as the principal deity and the {{ill|Myōken Mandala|ja|妙見曼荼羅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Myōken Mandala|qq=}} featuring {{ill|Myōken Bosatsu|ja|妙見菩薩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Myōken Bosatsu|qq=}}. These mandalas are central to rituals and ceremonies that honor the year's guiding star (当年星, tōnenjō)<ref>"Tōnenjō" is also referred to as "Tōnen Zokusei" (当年属星).</ref> and the natal star (本命星, honmyōjō).<ref>Although the term "honmyōsei" is also used in {{ill|Nine Star Ki|ja|九星気学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nine Star Ki|qq=}}, in this context it refers to stars from the {{ill|Big Dipper|ja|北斗七星|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Big Dipper|qq=}} and the {{ill|Nine Luminaries|ja|九曜星|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nine Luminaries|qq=}}, rather than the nine stars of Ki astrology.</ref>

Originally, this ritual was part of the {{ill|Taoist|ja|道教|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taoist|qq=}} Winter Solstice festival and had no relation to {{ill|Indian Buddhism|ja|インドの仏教|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Indian Buddhism|qq=}}. However, it was later incorporated into Esoteric Buddhism, where it was adapted and reinterpreted within a Buddhist framework.

In Esoteric astrology, as represented by the Star Mandala, both esoteric rituals and celestial astrology form the core principles. One of the nine {{ill|Navagraha|ja|九曜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Navagraha|qq=}} stars or the seven stars of the Big Dipper is assigned as a person's natal star (本命星), believed to govern their destiny.

The star that influences a person's fortune for the year is called the "Tōnen Zokusei" (当年属星). The ritual aims to honor these stars, pray for individual well-being, and eliminate misfortunes. Various temples across Japan hold Hoshi Matsuri and Star Memorial ceremonies.

